feedback.fq3:
All the visualizations had their advantages, but there were disadvantages to each of them:

In the first visualization, often the highlighted nodes would be too small to tell where it was, and it is hard to tell what is going on even a little bit away from the center. Additionally, the dramatic curves in the edges made it feel cluttered. That said, I found it the easiest to control, and very intuitive.

The second visualization was a great idea, but I found it very hard to control (particularly the panning), and occasionally, double clicking or hovering would not work properly and would (i believe) send me to the back of the "sphere" or highlight an unseen node. Additionally, if the highlighted node was not in the circular space to begin with, it was impossible to know where it would be.

The third visualization was the most intuitive, naturally, but the controls could be improved by making it more responsive and less slow and floaty. I also had the same problem as the second visualization, where I wouldn't know where the second highlighted node was if it wasn't initially on screen.

I'm Hamlet Taraz; Jacob Miller knows me, feel free to reach out if you have questions!

{"fq5":"3","fq6":"1","fq7":"1","fq8":"2","fq9":"1","fq1":"There were 2 general questions: 1) find the most frequent degree of the highlighted nodes and 2) find the shared neighbors.

For the first, I simply counted each, but I realized half-way through that I can simply see the approximate number of edges much quicker: 3 nodes have 1 edge vs. 1 node with 12 edges. Essentially, there are 3 nodes with that 1 edge, which is the quickest way to count, and then confirm that 3 is the majority of the set of highlighted nodes.

For the second, I used the hover feature to highlight both nodes' edges. Intuitively, nodes that are "between" the two highlighted nodes are generally shared, but there were some nodes that were outside of that "between" area which had me cluster generally then count that cluster, then verify that count with the other highlight.","fq2":"No.","fq4":"The only problem with the visualizations if if there are 3 nodes on 1 line, then the hover feature wouldn't allow us to discriminate between whether a node was connected or not.

For instance, let there be 3 nodes on a (nonexistent) line: A, B, C. A is on the left and C is on the right, with B in between. Let there be an edge between A and C. Let A and B also be highlighted. If you were to hover over A, then you would not be able to tell if there was an edge between A and C."}
